  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations regarding anti-money laundering (AML) efforts. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n- Reporting unusual financial activities\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting cash transactions above certain thresholds\n- Maintaining detailed transaction records\n\n3. Compliance Regulations\n- Following Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) guidelines\n- Implementing Know Your Customer (KYC) procedures\n- Conducting regular internal audits\n- Training employees on AML protocols\n\n4. Risk Assessment\n- Identifying potential money laundering risks\n- Developing risk management strategies\n- Implementing robust screening processes\n\n5. International Compliance\n- Adhering to global AML standards\n- Cooperating with international financial oversight organizations\n- Screening against international sanctions lists\n\n6. Potential Penalties\n- Significant financial fines\n- Regulatory sanctions\n- Potential criminal prosecution for non-compliance\n\nThese obligations are designed to prevent financial crimes and ensure transparency in financial systems.",
